'Hiberno-Saxon manuscripts' are those manuscripts made in the British Isles from
about 500 CE to about 900 CE in England, but later in Ireland and elsewhere, or
those manuscripts made on the continent in scriptoria founded by Irish or Anglo-
Saxon missionaries and which are stylistically similar to the manuscripts
produced in the British Isles. It is almost impossible to separate Anglo-Saxon,
Irish, Scottish and Welsh art at this period, especially in manuscripts; this
art is therefore called Insular art. See also insular script. For English
manuscripts produced after 900, see the List of illuminated Anglo-Saxon
manuscripts.
